Kyle Maurisak  [12:15 PM]
Carla and I have been discussing the future of Arbiter deploys and wanted to get a temp check on how this group was feeling.

I personally think that deploying commits individually with CD is an inherently less risky process than a multi-commit release branch deploy cadence. That said, given the current hoops we have to jump through to deploy, which is slowing down our delivery time substantially, we are falling into this pattern where we end up deploying multiple commits at a time regardless. This ends up being a riskier process than both options because we have the organization and structure of a single-commit CD deployment, but are batching commits. There's no meaningful tagging, which means a deploy could be labeled with a single commit sha abc123 in tagged telemetry, but it may contain commits abc123, def245, ghi777, etc. It leaves us in a place with worse observability/auditability and an overall lower sense of awareness amongst the team as to when code is being shipped and what code is included in that shipment.

So long as this manual approval process is in place, I think it actually makes sense to move towards a scheduled deploy cadence. I'm curious to get others' thoughts.

